I realize it&#39;s a little late for my reply, but I think @greg-449 is pointing you in the right direction. I detect changed files in my plugin.

In terms of a generified solution around ```IResourceChangeListener```, you want something like this:

```
ResourcesPlugin.getWorkspace().addResourceChangeListener(
		new IResourceChangeListener() {

			@Override
			public void resourceChanged(final IResourceChangeEvent event) {
				IResourceDelta delta = event.getDelta();
				IResourceDeltaVisitor visitor = new IResourceDeltaVisitor() {

					@Override
					public boolean visit(IResourceDelta delta) throws CoreException {

						IResource res = delta.getResource();

						switch (delta.getKind()) {
														
							case IResourceDelta.CHANGED:
								// file modified?
								if ((delta.getFlags() &amp; IResourceDelta.CONTENT) != 0) {
									// file content changed - do what you need to here
								}
								break;
													
							default:
								break;
						}
						return true;
					}
				};

				try {
					delta.accept(visitor);
				} catch (CoreException e) {
					LOGGER.error(&quot;Error checking IResourceDelta visitor&quot;, e);
				}

			}
		}, IResourceChangeEvent.POST_CHANGE
);
```

I can tell you that where file content modification occurs and is detected through something based on the above code, you will have to notify your own custom tracker for each resource in the project. It sounds like you would then query your tracker to identify the comprehensive list of changed files. 

It&#39;s worth keeping in mind that if a user clicks &quot;Save&quot; or uses the equivalent shortcut, the file will no longer be &#39;dirty&#39; and the above needs augmenting to detect and notify your tracking code of that. Whether that means you maintain a list of &#39;dirty&#39; ```IResource``` and remove them from your tracker as they are saved is up to you. In my case, I extended the above to detect user inactivity on changed files after a configurable time, then programmatically save &#39;dirty&#39; files and perform an additional activity on them. 

Detecting a file has been saved can be challenging. For me, it was enough to know a file was &#39;dirty&#39; and then no longer &#39;dirty&#39; - so this transition was indicative of either the file being saved, or reverted through SCM.

