I have concerns about your code, but here&#39;s a bit of syntatic sugar that I think handles your immediate problem.  Note that in Java a &quot;pointer&quot; is often just a SAM -- a class with a Single Abstract Method.  In this case I just used Runnable for the SAM.

    public class RunnableLooper implements Runnable {
       
       private State someState;
       private Runnable runMe;
    
       public RunnableLooper( State someState, Runnable runMe ) {
          this.someState = someState;
          this.runMe = runMe;
       }
       
       @Override
       public void run() {
          // stuff
          runMe.run();
          // etc.
       }
       
       public static void main( String[] args ) {
          State menu = new MenuState();
          State.setState(menu);
          State.getState().init();

          RunnableLooper runLoopA = new RunnableLooper( menu, menu::tick );
          RunnableLooper runLoopB = new RunnableLooper( menu, menu::render );
          
          Thread t1 = new Thread( runLoopA );
          t1.start();
          Thread t2 = new Thread( runLoopB );
          t2.start();
       }
    }
    
    class State {
       public void tick(){}
       public void render(){}
    }

If you have an older version of Java that doesn&#39;t support method references (`state::render`), then you&#39;ll have to manually make a pair of anonymous classes that do the same thing.

